{
  "text": "After phorbol ester treatment, HL-60 and U937 cells did not achieve a phenotype similar to that observed on monocytes obtained from peripheral blood of normal donors. We observed an enhancement in CD11a, CD11b and CD11c antigen expression consistent with the increased steady state levels of each respective message, as also shown by other authors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, the CD14 molecule, which is the endotoxin receptor highly expressed in human monocytes [CITATION_4] , was not induced upon PMA exposure of both cells. These data agree with those reported by some authors (30,31) but not with those reported by others [CITATION_5] . Various factors might be involved in these different responses such as source of serum and inducer concentration, in addition to differences occurring in cells during repeated passages. As a matter of fact, we observed that a slight proportion of U937-uninduced cells already expressed the CD14 antigen as reported by Hewison et al. [CITATION_6] , but not by Gidlund et al. [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
